# altastata-jupyter container: HPCS mounts are required

When starting or restarting the `altastata-jupyter` Docker container, the gRPC
server inside the container reads HPCS files referenced by user properties:

- `hpcs-yaml-path` (default in user_properties: `/etc/ep11client/grep11client.yaml`)
- `hpcs-priv-key-blob-path` (default: `/home/jovyan/hpcs-privkey.blob`)

These files live on the host (outside the repo) and are NOT in the committed
`docker-compose.yml`. They are bind-mounted via a personal, gitignored
override at `containers/jupyter/docker-compose.override.yml`. Compose merges
the override file when it's passed explicitly with `-f`.

## CRITICAL: mount the POPULATED grep11client.yaml, not the placeholder

There are usually two `grep11client.yaml` files on the host. They look similar.
Only one has real HPCS values (instance ID, address, apikey); the other is a
template with `<your-...>` placeholders. Mounting the placeholder one makes the
GREP11 client fail silently to load, which causes the server to fall through
to the PKCS#11 (.so) branch — that branch needs `pkcs11-grep11-arm64.so` which
doesn't exist on Mac, so `AuthService.Login` rejects every login as
`UNAUTHENTICATED "Invalid credentials"` (the real exception is hidden from
the client and only visible in `/tmp/altastata-grpc-server.log`).

Before mounting, verify the YAML is populated:

```bash
rg -c '<your-' /path/to/grep11client.yaml   # should print 0
```

For Serge's accounts, the populated file is
`mycloud/altastata-admin/grep11client.yaml` (NOT `altastata-core/...`).

## Always use BOTH compose files

Run the container with both `-f` flags so the override is merged:

```bash
ARCH=arm64 VERSION=2026e_latest docker compose \
  -f containers/jupyter/docker-compose.yml \
  -f containers/jupyter/docker-compose.override.yml \
  up -d
```

After the container starts, verify the HPCS mounts before declaring success:

```bash
docker inspect altastata-jupyter --format \
  '{{range .Mounts}}{{.Source}} -> {{.Destination}}{{println}}{{end}}' \
  | rg -i 'hpcs|grep11'
```

If the override file is missing, do NOT silently fall back to the main compose
alone — calls like `from_credentials(..., transport="grpc")` for HPCS accounts
will fail with `FAILED_PRECONDITION: HPCS configuration errors: ... not found`.
Instead, recreate the override with the user's real host paths for
`grep11client.yaml` and `hpcs-privkey.blob`, then bring the stack up.
